<Document>
<name>Côte d'Azur Corniches</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Côte d'Azur Corniches</h2><p><i>France · Cannes to Menton via Nice and the three corniches</i></p><p><b>Three parallel cliff roads above the Mediterranean — Roman highway, Napoleonic route, Belle Époque promenade.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>56 km (35 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>4–6 hrs with stops</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–June and September–October</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Heavy summer traffic, narrow corniche curves, motorbike speed, parking impossible in Monaco</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>108</td></tr></table><hr><p>Three roads parallel each other above the Mediterranean: the Grande Corniche (highest, oldest, the Roman Aurelian Way), the Moyenne (most picturesque, where Grace Kelly drove), and the Basse (sea-level coast). The Grande was the route Napoleon took back from Elba in 1815. Hitchcock filmed To Catch a Thief on the Moyenne with Grace Kelly; ironically she died on it in 1982. Drive in shoulder season — July and August are gridlock. The view from Èze, 427 m above the sea, looking down on Cap Ferrat, is the postcard. Park outside Monaco and walk in (or take the train) — driving in the Principality is a fool's errand.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Antibes old town &amp; Picasso Museum</b> — Picasso lived and worked in the Château Grimaldi in 1946; the museum has 245 of his works donated by the artist himself. Antibes ramparts give a walking circuit.</li><li><b>Promenade des Anglais</b> — Built in the 1820s with funds raised by Nice's English winter community. 7 km of seafront walk; the Hôtel Negresco's pink dome is the architectural marker.</li><li><b>Villa Ephrussi de Rothschild (Cap Ferrat)</b> — 1912 pink Belle-Époque mansion. Nine themed gardens (French, Spanish, Florentine, Japanese, etc.) on a peninsula between two bays.</li><li><b>Èze Village</b> — 14th-century 'eagle's nest' village 427 m above the sea. Jardin Exotique on the summit — succulents and rare cacti among medieval ruins. Pedestrian-only.</li><li><b>Trophy of Augustus, La Turbie</b> — 6 BC Roman triumphal monument celebrating Augustus's subjugation of Alpine tribes. 50 m tall when complete; 35 m today. Roman names of all 45 conquered tribes inscribed.</li><li><b>Monte Carlo Casino</b> — 1863 Charles Garnier-designed casino. The Grand Prix street circuit weaves around it; even outside race week, the racing line is in the asphalt.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
